  "prompt": "I scored 336 in GRE along with 5.0 in analytical writing. My grade is just around 8.0. Which universities should I focus on?",
  "response": "Congratulations on your GRE score and analytical writing score! Based on your GRE score of 336 and a GPA of around 8.0, you have a competitive profile for many graduate programs. The specific universities you should focus on can vary depending on your field of study and program level (master's or doctoral).\n\nHere\u2019s a general guideline for universities that typically accept students with similar profiles:\n\n### Top Tier Universities\n1. **University of California, Berkeley**\n2. **University of Michigan, Ann Arbor**\n3. **California Institute of Technology (Caltech)**\n4. **University of Chicago**\n5. **Stanford University**\n6. **Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)**\n\n### Mid Tier Universities\n1. **University of California, San Diego**\n2. **University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign**\n3. **University of Washington**\n4. **University of Texas at Austin**\n5. **University of Southern California**\n6. **University of Wisconsin-Madison**\n\n### Reach Universities (depending on your field)\n1. **Harvard University**\n2. **Columbia University**\n3. **Princeton University**\n\n### Considerations \n- **Field of Study:** Specific programs within universities can vary widely in competitiveness. Some departments may consider GRE scores more heavily than others.\n- **Research Interests:** Identify universities that fit your research interests and check if faculty members are working in those areas.\n- **Funding Opportunities:** Look for universities with available funding for graduate students, especially if you're interested in research positions.\n- **Location:** Consider geographical preferences and living expenses, as these can significantly affect your overall experience. \n\n### Next Steps\n1. **Research Programs:** Identify programs that align with your career goals and academic interests.\n2. **Contact Faculty:** Reach out to professors to express your interest in their work and inquire about potential opportunities.\n3. **Prepare Application Materials:** Focus on crafting a strong statement of purpose, obtaining good letters of recommendation, and showcasing any relevant experience.\n\nMake sure to check the specific admission requirements for each university and program you're considering, as they can vary. Good luck with your admissions process!",
